Firstly, the food was far from what I expected. The ingredients seemed to be of low quality and lacked freshness. The rice was dry and clumpy, the meat was overcooked and lacked flavor, and the vegetables were wilted and unappetizing. It was clear that the food was not prepared with care and attention to detail.

Additionally, the hygiene of the restaurant was a major concern. The tables were sticky and dirty, and there was a noticeable lack of cleanliness in the dining area. The floors were littered with food crumbs and the condiment station was messy and disorganized. It seemed as though the staff had not properly cleaned or maintained the restaurant.

Furthermore, the overall atmosphere was uninviting. The restaurant was dimly lit and had a stale odor. The seating was uncomfortable and the overall ambiance was far from welcoming. It was not an enjoyable place to dine in.

Overall, my experience at Chipotle was extremely disappointing. The food was of poor quality and the cleanliness of the restaurant was lacking. I would not recommend this particular Chipotle location based on my experience.

Iâ€™m talking about a very specific type of judgement that I feel is super counter-productive. Recently Iâ€™ve noticed an increase in judgement around how people contribute to humanity. We should all be doing our part. But when it goes too far, it becomes toxic. Someone donates to a cause and the response is, â€œthatâ€™s not enough.â€ Someone highlights an issue and the response is, â€œwhat about xyz.â€ Someone experiences an ounce of joy during tragedy and the response is, â€œmust be nice!â€ Iâ€™ll be vulnerable and share that it happens to me all the time. I can literally spend an entire month raising funds for girls in need, but that effort will be dismissed in seconds because I didnâ€™t post an IG story about another issue that Iâ€™m not as familiar with. I donâ€™t think we should be performative.Iâ€™m not sure what the goal of this energy is. To foster a culture in which people feel nervous and hesitant to give what they can doesnâ€™t feel productive to me. Mumbai got me like ğŸ˜ Itâ€™s been 4 years since Iâ€™ve visited India because the pandemic cancelled all my plans in 2019. I usually visit 1-2 times a year and this has been the largest gap of not doing so in my career. Travelling is a privilege. And itâ€™s one I prioritize working towards because I think travelling is responsible for a lot of my greatest strengths as a person. Namely, travelling so much has taught me to become adaptable and to recognize that your way, isnâ€™t the only way. The reality is that we all grow up in a bubble, in which people talk a certain way, work a certain way, respect or disrespect people a certain way and problem solve a certain way. And it becomes very easy to think that way is the only and right way. But itâ€™s not. And while I do strongly believe that there is much work to do in every country in the world, India included, to improve on issues like gender equality, thatâ€™s not the same as believing every part of another country or culture should operate in a way youâ€™re familiar with. Iâ€™m used to doing business via email. This past week I learned to adapt to Whatâ€™s App. Iâ€™m used to LA traffic and this past week I adapted because I experienced Mumbai traffic ğŸ˜… And Iâ€™m accustomed to alone time and slightly more personal space (a privilege in itself) but when youâ€™re in the most populated country in the world, you have to adapt. And my favourite, Iâ€™m used to saying â€œyes, no or maybeâ€ and now Iâ€™ve adapted and I have a head nod for every emotion. No words needed. We can become so used to making our surroundings suitable for us, which is a lovely luxury that people should practice if they can. I certainly do. But travelling reminds me that we also need to have the ability to adjust and pivot if the situation calls for it. And the situation often does in life, in relationships and in business. PROTOCOLS: THE KEY TO PRODUCTIVITY  TO RELAXATIONâ€¢ -On the Huberman Lab podcast, we often talk about protocols. The reason for using that word as opposed to â€œhacksâ€ or tools, or some other descriptor is that a â€œprotocolâ€ implies a set list of steps to carry out that are known to be effective.
